Dogs trained for roles like sentry, scout, messenger, and mine detection, with scout dogs being especially vital in alerting troops to enemy approaches.

Yesterday, I sat down with the incredible team at @MannaFoodCenter in Gaithersburg, where dedicated staff and volunteers are working every day to make sure families don’t go hungry. Right now, 4,400 families are on a six-week waiting list for a box of food. This is a heartbreaking reality that’s only going to get worse with the Administration’s decision to slash $1 billion in food assistance.

Manna has relied on the now-eliminated Local Food Purchase Assistance Cooperative Agreement Program to provide 12,000 pounds of fresh, nutritious food to families every day. With this funding gone, food banks across Maryland are facing an even bigger challenge at a time when one in three children in our state already go to bed hungry. Food is not a partisan issue—everyone needs to eat. We must fight to protect these vital programs in Congress and ensure no family in our state goes hungry.

Name: Fitzpatrick, Brian K.
text:
One of the major problems in America today is the political parties themselves. They are inherently divisive by their very nature. American citizens largely agree on 80%+ of issues.  They just want our government to function the same pragmatic way as do our businesses, our families and our personal relationships.  It is the political party structure itself, dividing “Red versus Blue” and “Democrat versus Republican,” that creates barriers between us and halts so much needed progress. It’s why I’m so proud to Co-Chair the Bipartisan @ProbSolveCaucus with my friend & colleague, @RepTomSuozzi.  Together, we seek to advance a very different model and a refreshing new change, a coalition of pragmatic and reasonable centrists from all walks of life, and with a variety of perspectives, to respectfully collaborate together, to see the world through the other person’s eyes, and to find common ground. It is the duty of every leader to be a bridge, not a wedge. This must be reflected in both our words and our actions. This is far and away the most critical ingredient to preserve our democracy.

Name: Fitzpatrick, Brian K.
text:
National Rural Letter Carriers’ Association President Don Mason joined us on Capitol Hill for a critical discussion on how we can better support the letter carriers who keep America’s mail moving—especially through my Protect Our Letter Carriers Act, which prioritizes their safety on the job.

For over 120 years, the @NRLCA has been a steadfast champion for letter carriers—advocating for their rights, safety, and the essential role they play in keeping America connected. Every day, these dedicated workers navigate all conditions to ensure mail and vital deliveries reach millions of Americans. But while they show up for us without fail, growing threats to their safety demand that we do the same for them. That’s why I’m pushing to pass this critical legislation—because no letter carrier should have to risk their safety simply for doing their job.

Thank you, Don, for your leadership and commitment. I look forward to working together to get this bill across the finish line and deliver the protections our letter carriers deserve.

Name: Jackson, Jonathan L.
text:
BREAKING: Congressman Jonathan L. Jackson Applauds Federal Judge’s Order to Reinstate Federal Workers Unlawfully Fired by Elon Musk

Washington, D.C. (March 13, 2025) — Today, Congressman Jonathan L. Jackson (IL-01) released the following statement in response to a federal judge’s ruling ordering the immediate reinstatement of federal employees unjustly terminated by Elon Musk and DOGE, including workers in the Department of Defense, the Department of Treasury, and the Department of Veterans Affairs:

“This ruling is a victory for working families, the rule of law, and the fundamental rights of our nation’s public servants. Across Illinois’ First Congressional District, thousands of federal employees, including VA nurses, postal workers, and transit safety inspectors, serve our communities with dedication. The unlawful terminations orchestrated by Elon Musk and rubber-stamped by the Trump-Musk Administration were a direct attack on these workers and their families.

“The court’s decision is clear: these public servants must be reinstated immediately. That includes the many essential employees in Illinois who help provide critical services—from maintaining our national parks to ensuring that our veterans receive the care they deserve. These are real people with real families, and their livelihoods should never have been jeopardized for political gain.

“I stand with my colleagues on the Oversight Committee in holding the Trump-Musk Administration accountable for their blatant disregard of labor laws. We will not allow their reckless and unlawful actions to undermine the stability of our federal workforce. In Illinois alone, over 8,000 federal employees contribute daily to essential services, and I will continue fighting to protect their jobs, their rights, and their dignity.”

Name: Fitzpatrick, Brian K.
text:
It was a pleasure to sit down with my friend Montu Patel of Innovative Hospitality Management in Doylestown as part of my ongoing work with local business owners, hospitality workers, and community leaders—alongside the Asian American Hotel Owners Association (AAHOA)—to strengthen our local economy and ensure the long-term success of the hospitality and travel industries. These industries are more than just economic drivers; they are the backbone of our communities, providing jobs, supporting local businesses, and fostering growth across PA-1.

Since its founding in 1989, AAHOA has grown into the world’s largest hotel owners association, representing an incredible 60% of U.S. hotels. Every night, 3.5 million guests stay in member-owned hotels, fueling job creation, boosting tourism, and investing in the places we call home.

To keep these businesses thriving, we must tackle workforce challenges, advance policies that spur economic growth, and provide tax relief that empowers small businesses and workers alike. Thank you, Montu, for your leadership—I look forward to continuing to work alongside you and all our PA-1 entrepreneurs to ensure PA-1 remains a place where businesses, workers, and families can prosper.

I will be voting ‘No’ on cloture and on the Republican continuing resolution.

A continuing resolution will allow President Trump to continue doing what he’s doing.

Looting our government to pay for tax cuts for billionaires.

Conducting a witch hunt against our patriotic civil servants — people who work on behalf of our veterans, people who work on behalf of our students, people who work on behalf of our domestic violence survivors.

Threatening to cut Social Security benefits, to cut Medicaid.

Causing the markets to crash by starting a trade war with our allies that will raise prices on goods and impact the pocketbooks of everyday Americans.

To allow the President to continue what he’s doing would be in direct contradiction with my mandate — to fight for Marylanders.

We have a unique opportunity at this moment to course correct and pass a clean, bipartisan funding bill that would address some of these concerns and mistakes. That is what Marylanders need and deserve in this moment of chaos.

Republicans control the White House, Senate, and House of Representatives. Whatever happens next is squarely on them.

Name: Self, Keith
text:
Since Schumer Shutdown is trending…a reminder of his own words:
 
September 16, 2024: “If the government shuts down, it will be average Americans who suffer most. A government shutdown means seniors who rely on Social Security could be thrown into chaos as the Social Security Administration limits certain services, like benefit verifications or fixing errors in payments. Our veterans could see regional VA offices shut down and support services put on halt. Some of our military service members could be forced to work without pay. Families who benefit from WIC and other nutrition programs could see benefits halted. And a shutdown would shake the confidence of our economic recovery, something we can’t possibly afford at a time like this.”

Name: Fitzpatrick, Brian K.

As a proud Irish American and descendant of Irish immigrants, I know the story of the Irish in America is not just about finding a new home—it’s about building one. They arrived with little but gave everything, shaping our cities, defending our nation, crafting our laws, and driving innovation. Their true strength lay not just in their labor, but in their unshakable faith in America’s promise. This museum will honor that legacy—preserving the past while educating and inspiring future generations—ensuring that the indomitable Irish spirit remains a defining force in our nation’s story.

Thank you to my colleagues, Friends of Ireland Caucus Co-Chairs @RepRichardNeal and @MikeKellyPA for joining me on this important initiative to celebrate and preserve our shared heritage.

Name: Courtney, Joe
text:
The passing of Congressman Raúl Grijalva is a loss that is felt all across our country, even in eastern Connecticut. In 2007, when I was the freshman Member of Connecticut’s Second District, Raúl managed passage in the U.S. House of Representatives of the Eight Mile River Wild and Scenic Designation bill that Senator Chris Dodd and I cosponsored and was signed into law by President George Bush. 

I will never forget how Raúl came to my assistance when the bill faced an unexpected partisan roadblock, and we worked together to secure its passage.

He was a tenacious warrior for protecting our national parks, natural monuments, and wild and scenic rivers, like the mighty Eight Mile River. We also sat side-by-side on the House Committee on Education and Labor for over a decade. He and I shared wonderful ‘sidebar’ jokes and comments, which he muttered at the same time he doodled intricate designs on his notepad during long, sometimes arduous, hearings.

He was a great Member of Congress and a great person. I extend my deepest condolences to Raúl’s family and hope their memories of him will be a blessing. I know my memory of him will always be a blessing for me.

Name: Scott, Robert C. "Bobby"
text:
I was deeply saddened to learn of the passing of my friend and colleague, @RepRaulGrijalva. We sat next to each other for many years on the Committee on Education and Workforce, and I could always rely on him for a sense of optimism and humor while in the midst of some of the toughest legislative fights.

In addition to being a proficient and talented doodler, he was a champion for his constituents and environmental justice for all. He was a fierce defender of unions and civil rights in the workplace. He was powerful advocate for universal education and child nutrition, and he also pushed to expand funding to support English as a Second Language (ESL) programs and students with disabilities. Name: Barragán, Nanette Diaz
text:
Heartbroken by the passing of my friend and colleague, Congressman Raúl Grijalva.
 
Raúl was not only a staunch advocate for the people of his district—he was a relentless champion for justice, for our environment, and for the rights of working families across this country. As Chair of the House Natural Resources Committee, he led with passion and principle, never wavering in the fight to protect our public lands, environmental justice communities, and Indigenous communities. I was honored to serve on the committee under his leadership when I first came to Congress and learned so much from his example. He was a tremendous leader on environmental justice legislation, and worked with me to pass legislation on climate justice grants and urban parks. His mentorship, wisdom, kindness, and dedication will never be forgotten.
 
My heart is with his family, loved ones, and the countless people whose lives he touched.

Name: Garcia, Sylvia R.
text:
I’m heartbroken to hear about the passing of my friend, Congressman Raúl Grijalva, after his battle with cancer.

Raúl was a force for good, a champion for Native communities, for our environment, for the God given right to clean water and clean air, and for the future of this country. He always reminded us that the fight was for the next generation, for the babies who would inherit this world. 

Raúl never lost sight of who he was fighting for. Whether he was fighting for Dreamers, workers, or tribal communities, he always led with his heart, humility, and an unshakeable commitment to doing what was right. I was proud to serve alongside him in the Congressional Hispanic Caucus.

My thoughts are with his family, his staff, and the Arizonans he dedicated his life to serving. His legacy will endure.

Name: Elfreth, Sarah
text:
I’m deeply saddened to learn of the passing of my colleague, Representative Raúl Grijalva.

His leadership on the Natural Resources Committee has preserved our precious lands, protected countless endangered species, and ensured the voices of Tribal Nations are represented in public land policy for generations to come. He leaves behind a tremendous legacy of environmental stewardship and action.

Tonight, I wanted to share his own words that have stuck with me: “We cannot back down from addressing the urgency of the climate crisis. We cannot leave the poor to fend for themselves against burgeoning corporate greed. We cannot allow our education, health care, and social security to be sold out so the rich can get richer. We must treat each other with dignity and respect, as neighbors, not enemies.” 

Let us carry the work forward.

Name: Hern, Kevin
text:
This week marks 5 years since the COVID was declared a national health emergency and the start of the detrimental lockdown policies that happened nationwide. 

Today, we know so much more. We would not - and will not - repeat those mistakes.

Name: Hern, Kevin
text: Anthony Fauci, the WHO, and other government bureaucrats preyed on the fear of Americans and convinced us to pull our children out of school, to close down our local businesses, to distance ourselves from the essential communities around us, and to trust unequivocally the word of unelected government bureaucrats.

Name: Hern, Kevin
text: The world is different today because of COVID-19. But the world is also different because of the knee-jerk, fear-based reaction meant to concentrate power in the bureaucracy and strip power from the individual and families.

Name: Hern, Kevin
text: 5 years later, we are still uncovering the true repercussions of these decisions.

Name: Hern, Kevin
text: An entire generation grew up without socialization outside their home or their screens. Businesses who were long-established in their communities shuttered forever. Many Americans lost their jobs. Supply chains overwhelmingly shifted overseas and we have not been able to claw that back. Government spending ballooned to catastrophic new highs.

Name: Hern, Kevin
text:
We will be dealing with these consequences for years to come. 

What’s important for our leaders moving forward is a commitment to never allowing this to happen again.

Name: Hern, Kevin
text:
Never again will we cede our authority to unelected bureaucrats.

Never again will we forbid Americans from participating in their local economy and community.

Never again will we force businesses to close at no fault of their own. 

Never again will we strip our students of the critical learning and socialization that happens in an in-person environment.

Name: Hern, Kevin
text:
I applaud the Trump Administration for their work to uncover and de-classify the buried secrets of the pandemic. 

We are making tremendous progress to protect Americans and ensure this never happens again.

Name: Clyburn, James E.
text:
I'm saddened to learn of the passing of my colleague — Congressman Raúl Grijalva. 

Grijalva proudly served his constituents in southern Arizona and was a champion for preserving our natural resources, fighting for bilingual education in our schools, and safeguarding our nation's natural treasures for over two decades. He cared about protecting this nation's stories, memories, and legacy through conservation and natural heritage. 

As Chair and Ranking Member of the House Natural Resources Committee throughout his time in Congress, his voice, vision, and passion for public lands and climate action will be deeply missed. 
 
My prayers are with his family and loved ones.

Name: Collins, Mike
text:
On #ThisDayInHistor in 1964, Jack Ruby, a Dallas nightclub owner, was sentenced to death for the murder of Lee Harvey Oswald, the accused assassin of President John F. Kennedy. 

The verdict, the first televised in U.S. history, followed Ruby’s fatal shooting of Oswald on live TV during a police transfer. Ruby claimed grief over JFK’s death spurred him, but the jury dismissed his defense. Linked to organized crime and Dallas police favors, Ruby’s conviction was overturned in 1966. He died before a retrial. 

The Warren Commission found no evidence of a conspiracy, yet many believe Ruby’s actions hid a larger plot.

Name: Carter, Troy A.
text:
Cloture is a rule in the U.S. Senate used to end a debate and force a vote on a bill or nomination.

Think of it like this: If senators keep talking about an issue to delay or block a decision (this is called a filibuster), cloture is the way to stop them. It takes 60 votes to pass cloture and move forward. Once cloture is approved, debate is limited, and the Senate must take a final vote.

In short, cloture prevents endless talking and makes sure decisions get made.

—TAC

Name: Fitzpatrick, Brian K.
text:
Each week, we share stories of remarkable individuals from across our district who are making a difference. This week, we shine a light on an incredible man shaping the minds of the next generation, fostering curiosity, and inspiring a lifelong love of discovery—meet this week's Hometown Hero, Dave Curry.
 
For 33 years, Dave Curry has done more than teach Earth and space science—he has transformed how students experience it. As an educator at Newtown Middle School in the Council Rock School District, he has made geoscience not just a subject, but an adventure—one that empowers young minds to see the world differently, think critically, and explore with purpose. His extraordinary commitment to innovation and excellence in science education has earned him the prestigious 2025 American Geosciences Institute’s National Edward C. Roy Jr. Award for Excellence in K-8 Earth Science Teaching, a national recognition that reflects his profound impact on the field.
 
Dave's innovative approach to education is best exemplified by the multi-month, computer-based lab exercise he developed, which builds on NASA’s Sally Ride EarthKAM program. Through this immersive, hands-on experience, his students don't just learn about the Earth—they become scientists, working with real satellite imagery and data to study weather systems, geologic processes, coastal erosion, and plate tectonics. They analyze how natural forces shape the planet, engage in the same methodologies used by geoscientists, and discover firsthand how science can solve real-world problems.
 
This is the power of a truly exceptional educator—one who doesn’t just teach facts but opens doors to possibility and excitement. Dave's students see themselves in the work of scientists, engineers, and innovators. They aren’t just absorbing knowledge; they’re developing the skills, confidence, and curiosity that will lead them to shape the future.
 
Beyond the classroom, Curry’s passion for science education knows no bounds. His leadership as a mentor for the American Meteorological Society’s DataStreme graduate courses, his role as a science fair sponsor, and his deep engagement in professional organizations reflect his unwavering dedication to ensuring students have access to the very best in Earth and space science education.
 
Our teachers are heroes; they are the architects of the future and the catalysts of discovery. At a time when our nation faces a growing teacher shortage, the need for passionate, innovative, and skilled educators has never been more critical. The success of our next generation hinges on the excellence, dedication, and mentorship of educators like Dave Curry—those who go beyond the curriculum to ignite imaginations, fuel ambition, and shape the scientists, problem-solvers, and visionaries of tomorrow.
 
Please join me in congratulating Dave on the well-deserved recognition of his work, and thanking him, along with all our dedicated PA-1 teachers, for their selfless efforts in guiding our next generation of leaders. Dave, we applaud you and thank you—you are shaping the future, one inspired student at a time.

text:
Donald Trump and Elon Musk have offered the Congress a false choice between a government shutdown or a blank check that makes a devastating assault on the well-being of working families across America.

I salute Leader Hakeem Jeffries for his courageous rejection of this false choice, and I am proud of my colleagues in the House Democratic Caucus for their overwhelming vote against this bill.

Democratic senators should listen to the women. Appropriations leaders Rosa DeLauro and Patty Murray have eloquently presented the case that we must have a better choice: a four-week funding extension to keep government open and negotiate a bipartisan agreement.  

America has experienced a Trump shutdown before – but this damaging legislation only makes matters worse. Democrats must not buy into this false choice. We must fight back for a better way. Listen to the women, For The People.

Name: Davis, Donald G.
text:
Friday in the First

Sherry Fischlschwieger is a dedicated 33-year resident of Currituck County, an Army veteran, and a passionate 4-H and youth development agent with the North Carolina Cooperative Extension-Currituck County Center. With over 13 years of experience in 4-H programming, Sherry has made a significant impact on the area's youth. She empowers young people by offering hands-on opportunities in agriculture, STEM, leadership, and community service, helping them develop essential life skills, explore career paths, and contribute to their communities.

She is involved in local community services such as Meals on Wheels, the local food bank, and various youth-focused community service and citizenship projects. Her dedication to service has earned her the T.C. Blalock Young Agent Award. Sherry's unwavering commitment to her career and community highlights the power of hands-on learning and actively being involved in shaping the future of the East.

#FridaySpotlight

Name: Neal, Richard E.
text:
As we wrap up St. Patrick's week in D.C., I am grateful for the sanctity of the relationship between the U.S. and Ireland. Enduring more than a century, the relationship between our two nations is rooted in our strong ancestral ties and shared democratic values.

Two generations have now grown up not knowing the violence of the Troubles or living with a hard border. To think of where we were not too long ago and where we are now, I have no doubt that my ancestors would be proud of the Ireland we have today.

We will continue working to ensure the gains that have been achieved can be enjoyed by future generations to come, regardless of where on the island you live or what tradition you practice.

“Being up in Blueberry Hills [outside Unalakleet] with the most amazing sunset you could ever imagine, the moon shimmering off the glazed snow and the Northern Lights, I was thinking about Jerry Riley, Rick Mackey and Lance Mackey, all the great legends before me looking down on me and telling me I could do it. I just wanted to join that club with them.”

Jessie, you have entered that club of Alaskan legends.

Name: Mackenzie, Ryan
text:
Despite the attempt by some to take us back to the days of partisan gridlock, a clear, bipartisan majority in the U.S. Senate — including Sens. Fetterman and McCormick — joined those of us in the U.S. House who voted to keep the government open and deliver results that the American people are counting on. By funding the expedited deportation of criminals, supporting our military service members, and standing up for working families and seniors, we’ve shown what can be accomplished when we prioritize the needs of our citizens. 

The bipartisan continuing resolution largely keeps the government funded at 2024 levels but also includes critical new spending, including:

Major investments in national security and public safety
✅ $485 million to help clear the backlog of deportations.
✅ Expanded funding for cybersecurity.
✅ $5.8 billion for naval vessels.
✅ $750 million for air traffic controllers.

Support for veterans and service members
✅ $1.6 billion to fund the largest pay increase for junior enlisted soldiers in over 40 years.
✅ $6 billion in funding for veterans' healthcare.

Relief for seniors and working families
✅ Over $500 million for WIC
✅ $36 million for the Commodity Supplemental Food Program (food packages for seniors)

I am not going to vote for a partisan funding bill that makes deep cuts to essential government functions. This bill endangers the health of Americans by cutting $280 million from the National Institutes of Health; jeopardizes the state of Washington’s maritime economy by slashing the Army Corps of Engineers by 44 percent; and impacts our farmers by cutting $57 million from USDA’s important agriculture research facilities. A bipartisan congressional effort to finish all appropriations bills would have delivered better results for taxpayers.

Congress has the authority and responsibility to direct federal spending based on the needs of their constituents. Turning that work over to the White House puts important programs like NOAA experts working on salmon recovery or creating weather forecasts at risk.

Name: Collins, Mike
text:
On #ThisDayInHistory in 44 BC, Julius Caesar was assassinated in an event known as the Ides of March.

Caesar was murdered in the Senate House by about 60 conspirators, including Brutus and Cassius. Fearing that Caesar’s growing power threatened the Roman Republic, the conspirators ambushed him during a Senate meeting, stabbing him 23 times. The famous phrase 'Et tu, Brute?' (meaning 'And you, Brutus?') is often attributed to Caesar, expressing his shock at being betrayed by someone he considered an ally.

His death marked a dramatic turning point in Roman history, signaling the end of the Roman Republic and the rise of imperial rule.

According to the State Forestry Incident Commander, thanks to Mother Nature’s assistance, the fire lines cut yesterday, and the continued efforts of firefighting resources, the fire is not expected to progress any further.

Name: Fitzpatrick, Brian K.
text:
What an incredible night at the Bucks County St. Patrick’s Day Parade Committee Irish Ball! To be named Grand Marshal of this year’s parade was an honor beyond words—made even more meaningful knowing that 35 years ago, my father held this very title as the second-ever Grand Marshal. Standing in his footsteps, surrounded by friends, family, and this incredible community, was a powerful reminder that the Irish spirit is more than something we celebrate—it is something we live, breathe, and pass down through generations.

My deepest gratitude to President Brian Galloway, Vice President Liam Hennessy, Parade Director Harley Greene, Ann Soobie, the many volunteers, and all my Hibernian brothers and sisters whose dedication keeps this tradition alive. Your work and efforts ensure our heritage of resilience, unity, and faith continue to thrive.

Thank you to my dear friends, @SenatorMarkDaly, Chair of the Senate of Ireland, and @RepBrendanBoyle, for taking the time to join us—your presence made the night even more special. 

Grateful beyond words for this honor and for this extraordinary community. Wishing everyone a wonderful St. Patrick’s weekend! 🍀🇮🇪

Name: Espaillat, Adriano
text:
Congresswoman Nita Lowey was a barrier breaker and a champion for her constituents, the state of New York, and our nation. She welcomed me to Congress with open arms, and we had the opportunity to work closely as members of the New York Congressional Delegation, where I witnessed firsthand her tireless efforts to champion change and uplift women, minorities, and families.

As the first female chair of the House Appropriations Committee, Congresswoman Lowey was a trailblazer whose leadership left an indelible mark both domestically and internationally. She was a fierce advocate for women’s rights, securing critical funding for women’s health. Her leadership in foreign affairs strengthened America’s standing in the world, and her bipartisan work post-9/11 helped bolster national security and support for New York during one of its most challenging times.

I extend my heartfelt condolences to her family, her husband Stephen, and their children and grandchildren during this time of bereavement. We will remember fondly the legacy of inspiration and progress she leaves behind for each of us to follow.

📸 credit Elizabeth D Herman for The New York Times

Name: Espaillat, Adriano
text:
La congresista Nita Lowey fue una persona que rompió barreras y una defensora de sus constituyentes, del estado de Nueva York y de nuestra nación. Me recibió en el Congreso con los brazos abiertos y tuvimos la oportunidad de trabajar estrechamente como miembros de la Delegación de Congresistas de Nueva York, donde presencié de primera mano sus incansables esfuerzos por impulsar el cambio y promover el bienestar de las mujeres, las minorías y las familias.

Como la primera mujer presidenta del Comité de Asignaciones Presupuestarias de la Cámara, la congresista Lowey fue una pionera cuyo liderazgo dejó una huella imborrable tanto a nivel nacional como internacional. Fue una férrea defensora de los derechos de las mujeres, consiguiendo financiación crucial para la salud femenina. Su liderazgo en asuntos exteriores fortaleció la posición de Estados Unidos en el mundo, y su trabajo bipartidista después del 9/11 contribuyó a reforzar la seguridad nacional y el apoyo a Nueva York durante uno de sus momentos más difíciles.

Extiendo mis más sinceras condolencias a su familia, a su esposo Stephen, a sus hijos y nietos en este momento de duelo. Recordaremos con cariño el legado de inspiración y progreso que deja para que cada uno de nosotros lo siga.

Name: Whitehouse, Sheldon
text: I did a lot research into how a shutdown might play out, and there was lots to fear; not least that the Trump/Musk/Vought axis of MAGA extremists would love a shutdown, and want a long one, and use it to cruel advantage. What was there to fear?

Name: Whitehouse, Sheldon
text: MAGA extremists and their spineless Congress would decide what agencies or parts of agencies to bring back out of shutdown, and when. Defense, Homeland Security and the VA (with parts they don’t like removed) would likely come first.

Name: Whitehouse, Sheldon
text: The horrible stuff they’re now doing illegally and sloppily with their DOGE Musk-rats, they could do in shutdown mode under a veneer of legality, directed by Trump’s “Project 2025” OMB, with added executive powers from declaring an “emergency.”

Name: Whitehouse, Sheldon
text: In shutdown, executive powers are at their apex, including power to close whole departments and agencies and divisions, “Reduction in Force” all their personnel, and make massive cuts of programs and firings of people they deem “non-essential.”

Name: Whitehouse, Sheldon
text: But Senate Democrats had to handle actual shutdown dynamite. It was a different set of choices for my Senate colleagues. Shutdown or no shutdown was in our hands. Good people had to make hard choices between horrible alternatives.

Name: Whitehouse, Sheldon
text: I was willing to walk into that valley of government death to bring the battle to a head, make a clear break between sides, and (I believe) help brightly spotlight for voters the evil at work. But it’s reasonable to reach the other conclusion, and good people did.

Name: Whitehouse, Sheldon
text: But when would they bring the Department of Education back out of shutdown, or the EPA? Ever? What courts would they keep open for “essential” judicial functions (with Roberts’ blessing)? The MAGA-ized Fifth Circuit? Trump’s MAGA district judges?

Name: Whitehouse, Sheldon

Name: Whitehouse, Sheldon

On #ThisDayInHistory in 461, Saint Patrick, the patron saint of Ireland, died. 

Born in Roman Britain, he was kidnapped at 16 by Irish raiders and spent six years in slavery. After escaping, he returned to Britain, then had a vision calling him back to Ireland. Ordained a bishop, Patrick spent 40 years preaching Christianity, converting many, and building churches. 

St. Patrick’s death day became a religious holiday in Ireland, with church services and celebrations. The first St. Patrick’s Day parade occurred in 1601.

Name: Cloud, Michael
text:
The National Police Association Backs [Rep. Cloud's bill] the 287(g) Program Protection Act.

🧵of @NatPoliceAssoc's endorsement and what the 287(g) program is below:
https://t.co/uFh9tFt26a

Name: Cloud, Michael
text: "The 287(g) program—named for Section 287(g) of the Immigration and Nationality Act—is a product of the Illegal Immigration Reform and Immigrant Responsibility Act of 1996.

Name: Cloud, Michael
text: "The program has unfortunately been underutilized. Just 135 of approximately 18,000 state and local law enforcement agencies currently participate in the program, and no new agreements have been generated since 2021.

Name: Cloud, Michael
text: "The 287(g) Program Protection Act would amend the INA to strengthen this crucial program, ensure that it’s working as intended, and make it widely available to law enforcement agencies across the country.

Name: Cloud, Michael
text:
"This bill seeks to do the following:

1. Require ICE to approve new agreements with state and local police agencies within 90 days of application. The agency would be required to notify Congress when it issues a denial.

Name: Cloud, Michael
text: 3. Mandate the Department of Homeland Security to publish annual reports describing the program’s progress.

Name: Cloud, Michael
text:
4. Design a plan to recruit police agencies for participation in the program.

5. Provide funding to help local law enforcement agencies train officers and enforce the program.

Name: Cloud, Michael
text: 2. Prohibit the federal government from canceling current agreements with state and local police agencies unless a solid reason is provided. Agencies would be given an opportunity to challenge the decision.

Name: Cloud, Michael
text: "We have confidence that if this bill is passed, it would foster greater cooperation between ICE and local law enforcement agencies, which will ultimately aid in keeping our communities safe." — @NatPoliceAssoc

No court has found them guilty, and any one of the nearly 300 people targeted could be innocent of what they are accused. There is not a shred of evidence to suggest otherwise. Yet, on the word of Donald Trump alone and against the direct orders of a federal judge, this administration deported them to a foreign prison thousands of miles away. Then they sadistically applauded their humanitarian abuses in a highly produced video for their followers on social media.

And so, the question every American needs to ask today is the same question Americans asked during the internment of our Japanese-American neighbors during World War II, it is the same question Americans asked when lives and livelihoods were destroyed during the Red Scare, it is the same question that should be asked in response to every claim out of the president’s lying mouth: WHERE. IS. YOUR. PROOF? When this administration answers with silence, that will just confirm what we already know – according to Donald Trump, due process is now a relic of America’s past. Innocence is irrelevant, and so is the rule of law. Everything our Constitution stands for is second to what Donald Trump wants, and how hateful and cruel he feels on any given day.

If you think what this video represents will never reach your home, think again. Because when the Trump Administration continues their lawless crusade, very soon, they’ll have to turn to other groups to fill this president’s quota for human suffering. When that happens, you just might see your friend or neighbor in another video from this White House – it will call them a criminal, mock their misery, and celebrate their pain as a victory for Americans. You'll know the truth, but it won't matter. From now on, the White House decides what the truth is. 

These are dangerous times, folks. Look out for one another – because Donald Trump is always looking for new people to hurt.

Name: Fitzpatrick, Brian K.
text:
St. Patrick’s Day is more than just a date on the calendar—it is a celebration of the perseverance, sacrifice, and indomitable spirit of the Irish people. Our Irish ancestors came to America seeking opportunity, and in doing so, they helped shape, defend, and enrich this nation in ways too vast to measure. Their story is one of hardship and hope, struggle and triumph—woven into the very fabric of our country. 

Today, with nearly 2 million Irish Americans in Pennsylvania and millions more across the nation, that legacy endures. As the proud descendant of Irish immigrants and a steadfast Friend of Ireland, I am honored to introduce legislation to recognize St. Patrick’s Day as a federal holiday—a well-deserved tribute to the incredible impact of the Irish on the American story.

So raise a glass, wear your green, and celebrate the luck, legacy, and lasting influence of the Irish!

Happy St. Patrick’s Day, everyone! 🍀🇮🇪

Name: Mills, Cory
text:
I am proud to cosponsor H.R. 724, the CBO Show Your Work Act. This legislation works to ensure greater transparency and accountability within the legislative process. Floridians deserve to know how their tax dollars are spent and how policies that affect their lives are determined.

Introduced by @Rep_Davidson (OH-08), this bill requires the Congressional Budget Office (CBO) to disclose the fiscal and policy models they use to estimate proposed legislation's costs and economic impacts. These estimates play a crucial role in shaping our policies, and the American people deserve to understand the decision-making process behind them

I know Speaker Johnson supports it. Now we have a Republican Senate and a President in Donald J. Trump who will sign it. Let’s get this done.

The radical transgender movement will do everything they can to keep parents confused and scared. Listen to Chloe’s warning: Don’t let them. Stand firm. Protect your kids.

You can hear Chloe’s full story—and insight from whistleblower Dr. @EithanHaim—on my latest Hold These Truths episode. Available now wherever you get your podcasts.

Name: Fitzpatrick, Brian K.
text:
Spent an incredible afternoon with the 8th graders at Charles Boehm Middle School, and couldn’t be more impressed by their curiosity, thoughtfulness, and interest in civic engagement. 

We had a meaningful discussion about some of the biggest challenges facing our country, and their insightful  questions and ideas made it clear just how much they care about our community and future. Conversations like these underscore the value of civic engagement at a young age. When we equip students with the knowledge and opportunities to lead, they develop a deeper understanding of their role in shaping the future. 

A big thank you to Principal Hultquist and the exceptional teachers at Charles Boehm for fostering a culture of learning, leadership, and service. These students are already thinking critically and stepping up to make a difference, and I look forward to joining you again soon!

text:
Join me in celebrating two outstanding young leaders, Walter George Scarborough III of Troop 147 and Nathan Wapner of Troop 24, on earning the prestigious rank of Eagle Scout—an achievement that marks them as leaders of character, vision, and unwavering dedication to service.

Walter and Nathan’s dedication to service is evident in the impactful projects they led. Walter took on a vital initiative to support a local church food pantry, constructing a fully finished storage room—installing insulation, drywall, paint, spackle, and a door—ensuring the pantry can better serve families in need. While Nathan’s project focused on environmental conservation, designing and installing four fishing line disposal tubes at Loch Alsh Reservoir in Upper Dublin to protect wildlife and preserve our waterways.

These young men exemplify the highest ideals of Scouting, setting a standard of leadership and service that will inspire generations to come. Let’s all take a moment to congratulate them on this well-earned honor and their bright futures that lie ahead!

The Trump Administration is once again erasing the experiences and contributions of the brave men and women who answered the call to serve. Name: Collins, Mike
text:
On #ThisDayInHistory in 1325, Tenochtitlan was founded by the Aztecs.

Tenochtitlan was built on an island in Lake Texcoco after they saw an eagle eating a snake, as guided by their god. The city covered over 5 square miles with the Templo Mayor at the center, housing temples for gods and sites for sacrifices, including human ones.

In 1521, Spanish conquistadors captured Tenochtitlan after a 93-day siege. The city was destroyed, and Hernán Cortés began constructing Mexico City on its ruins, draining Lake Texcoco in the process.

Name: Panetta, Jimmy
text:
The American people have earned their Social Security benefits, and they need a federal government that ensures those benefits are delivered, promptly, efficiently, and without unnecessary obstacles. 

Unfortunately, this administration, under the direction of Elon Musk and Doge, is doing the exact opposite by gutting the Social Security Administration (SSA), slashing its workforce by 12%, and shutting down nearly 50 field offices.

Name: Panetta, Jimmy
text:
In California’s 19th Congressional District alone, over 140,000 people rely on Social Security, receiving $282 million in monthly benefits, including 120,000 retirees, 5,000 children, and 8,000 disabled workers. 

These cuts will directly impact them by increasing wait times, limiting access to services, and making it harder for them to receive the benefits they have earned.

Name: Panetta, Jimmy
text: As a member of Congress, I take pride in helping my constituents navigate the federal system, and I know many of my colleagues do too. Social Security casework is one of the most critical services we provide. We push the agency to get results, to cut through the red tape, and to ensure people get the benefits they are entitled to. But when this administration actively dismantles the SSA, I’m going to fight back with everything I can to protect the people I serve.

Name: Panetta, Jimmy
text: I stood with my colleagues demanding transparency from the Trump Admin and forcing a vote in committee for answers. The administration must provide Congress with details about what Elon Musk and DOGE are doing at SSA and why they are making these devastating cuts.

Name: Panetta, Jimmy
text: This administration is putting SSA in the wood chipper, and if we let them do it, we will be held accountable. It's past time we fulfill our constitutional duty, conduct real oversight, and stand up for our constituents. I will keep fighting to protect Social Security and the hardworking Americans who rely on it.

Since 1988, he has taken on numerous roles, including patrol officer, detective, crash reconstructionist, and field training officer. Throughout all these positions, one thing has remained constant: his dedication to protecting our community.

His leadership has helped shape a generation of officers, his expertise has contributed to the safety of our streets, and his service has made Warwick Township a better place. Please join me in congratulating Detective Corporal Paul Fox on his remarkable career, thanking him for his outstanding service, and wishing him the best as he embarks upon a well-deserved retirement!

Name: Harris, Mark
text:
The Founders never intended for a single rogue judge to be able to overturn executive actions.

The Judiciary was never meant to be the absolute authority on any given issue.

What did our Founders have to say about this? 🧵⤵️ https://t.co/Pl2bHFtQqp

Name: Harris, Mark
text:
Jefferson wrote in a letter to William Charles Jarvis: “You seem...to consider the judges as the ultimate arbiters of all constitutional questions: a very dangerous doctrine indee[d] and one which would place us under the despotism of an Oligarchy. Our judges are as honest as other men, and not more so. They have, with others, the same passions for party, for power, and the privileges of their corps.”

Judges are not immune to being swayed by their political beliefs, and thus should not be the sole authority on Constitutionality.

Name: Harris, Mark
text:
Thomas Jefferson in a letter to William Torrance wrote: “The…question, whether the judges are invested with exclusive authority to decide on the constitutionality of a law, has been heretofore a subject of consideration with me in the exercise of official duties. Certainly there is not a word in the Constitution which has given that power to them more than to the executive or legislative branches.”

The idea that courts have an exclusive right to declare laws unconstitutional comes from a misreading of Marbury v. Madison. Marbury stands for the proposition that the Constitution binds every branch of government, and each branch must follow it. Marbury should not be read to authorize judicial supremacy.

Name: Harris, Mark
text:
Jefferson, in a letter to George Hay, wrote: “But would the executive be independent of the judiciary, if he were subject to the commands of the latter, and to imprisonment from disobedience; if the several courts could bandy him from pillar to post, keep him constantly trudging from north to south and east to west, and withdraw him entirely from his constitutional duties?”

Our branches are not truly separate if, for instance, a president has to follow unlawful orders from the Judiciary.

Name: Harris, Mark
text:
In the same letter, Jefferson wrote: “[A judges’] power the more dangerous as they are in office for life, and not responsible, as the other functionaries are, to the elective controul. The Constitution has erected no such single tribunal knowing that, to whatever hands confided, with the corruptions of time & party it’s members would become despots.”

Judges are appointed for life subject to good behavior — this can be a way to insulate them from the political process, but it can also create complacency, entitlement, and pride, particularly if nobody seeks to check their unlawful rulings.

Name: Harris, Mark
text:
In Lincoln’s first inaugural address, he said: "The candid citizen must confess that if the policy of the Government upon vital questions affecting the whole people is to be irrevocably fixed by decisions of the Supreme Court, the instant they are made in ordinary litigation between parties in personal actions the people will have ceased to be their own rulers, having to that extent practically resigned their Government into the hands of that eminent tribunal."

Activist judges are a threat to our form of government when they take one person’s case and force their opinions on the whole country through nationwide injunctions.

Name: Harris, Mark
text:
In Jefferson’s letter to Charles Hammond in 1821, he wrote: “The germ of dissolution of our federal government is in the constitution of the federal Judiciary; an irresponsible body (for impeachment is scarcely a scare-crow) working like gravity by night and by day, gaining a little today and a little tomorrow, and advancing its noiseless step like a thief, over the field of jurisdiction, until all shall be usurped.”

Jefferson foresees the threat that an unchecked Judiciary can encroach on the authority of other branches.

Name: Harris, Mark
text:
President Trump is fulfilling his duty as Commander-in-Chief to protect America.

But he is being unlawfully hindered by a handful of activist judges. The issue is not a matter of personality or policy differences, but a genuine question about the role of the Judicial branch.

Congress must exercise its constitutional duty to oversee the inferior courts and defund, strip jurisdiction of, and impeach the rogue judges who are more interested in being judicial activists than supporting the Constitution and the rule of law.

Name: Horsford, Steven
text: 🚨Medicaid is a lifeline for Nevada-but funding is at risk. If federal Medicaid cuts go through,thousands could lose coverage. Here’s what you need to know. 🧵👇🏾

Name: Horsford, Steven
text: Federal Medicaid funding to Nevada was $4.3 BILLION in 2023 –making up 57% of all federal funding to the state.

Name: Horsford, Steven
text: Most of Nevada’s Medicaid costs are matched by the federal government at a 60% rate–known as the Federal Medical Assistance Percentage (FAMP).

Name: Horsford, Steven
text: What happens if Medicaid funding is slashed? Nevada will face impossible choices-who loses coverage? What benefits get cut?

Name: Horsford, Steven
text: For Medicaid expansion under the Affordable Care Act (ACT), the federal matching rate is even higher-90% for adults 19-64 who don’t qualify under other categories, like pregnancy.

Name: Horsford, Steven
text: Medicaid is a lean program. It has expanded to cover more people, but person spending growth has remained lower than other payers.

Name: Horsford, Steven
text:
With few options to fill the budget hole left by cuts, states will have to consider: 
❌ Reducing coverage for low-income families 
❌ Slashing benefits like prescription drugs & mental health care 
❌ Leaving more people uninsured & underinsured

Name: Horsford, Steven
text: This isn’t just a budget issue-it’s a public health crisis. Medicaid helps working families, seniors, and vulnerable communities. We can’t afford to lose it. HANDS OFF MEDICAID. #SAVEMEDICAID
